This symptom is characteristic of a problem with which Verant has been struggling since at least Kunark.  It's very easy to increase the damage output of a warrior, simply by adding a more potent weapon to the game.  It's much harder to improve casting classes, because once a spell is in the game it rarely ever changes.  Pre-60 wizards, for example, have largely the same damage efficiency as they've had since Kunark.  It's trivial to improve tools--it's much harder to improve (for want of a better term) art.  Level 50 warriors used to wield Ykeshas--now most level 10 warriors scoff at such.  Level 50 Wizards still use Ice Comet (or maybe Draught of Fire?  can't remember)  Wizards were among the first to realize this, as they neither melee nor help others to melee.  Clerics were some of the last casting classes to be affected, because complete heal is made more efficient as tanks get better hitpoint gear.  AA skills have helped somewhat, but the fundamental problem remains.<br>
<br>
A natural result of this is that monks must become  far and away the most potent class.  They gain as much in damage per second from new gear as do warriors, and mend becomes more potent as their hitpoint gear increases.  Indeed, this has already happened at the highest levels.  (Excluding AE groups, and with the advent of manaburn, some specific-kill encounters.)<br>
<br>
Bards get smacked with this problem twofold.  First, bards are an exception almost everywhere, so fixes for general casters will likely not apply to bards.  Second, bards wield weapons, so I suspect Verant will be tempted to boost bards simply by throwing nicer weapons at us and rendering us less and less distinctive from other melees as our songs become less and less significant.  Even simply adding instruments with higher modifiers would be something of a clumsy fix.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Power progression is independent of the progression of our utility. Would you prefer that they increase our power across the board relative to other classes at the cost of no longer being able to stack effects or use them sans mana, for instance?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
This would be bad, I agree, but it need not even be so extreme.  Giving us nicer weapons would increase our power and utility, but it still dissolves more and more of the nature of the class.  I want more useful and scalable songs, not just bigger swords and mallets.<br>
<br>
What are your views:<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Am I wrong about the technology versus art problem?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Have I complete misinterpreted this?  Do you see spell damage scaling with weapon damage, or if not, do you not see the mismatch as relevant?  Why?<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> If my view of the fundamental flaw is accurate, what can be done about it?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Is there a general solution that will help everyone?  If not, what can be done to fix it for bards?  Making hastes and slows truly stack, and making resistances greater than 200 meaningful would certainly help our utility--would that be enough? <p>Elianna<br>
